text: What I disliked from the trailer, and it goes without saying, they "teased" the whole movie into a trailer,  ..was that the creator says to him, "You can do whatever you want"  And then shows him going to parties, playing sports, and sleeping with women as conquests, racing expensive cars...  But there's always a catch. If anything, I realize they have to include the proclivities of celebrity life to attract the younger generations of people who need every pair of Nikes and Jordan's and all the new iPhones and iWatchs they need,   But if we had it my way, the true sci-fi thriller,  We would've seen him trying to find a cure for his cancer, even if his body didn't have it, then we would see that the corporation that does these mind transfers somehow caused his cancer, to trick him into funding the corporation with billions of dollars and then when his mind was erased as his donor body's memories resurface, the corporation would deem him useless or expendable.   Then they could do this with everyone they want to get rid of, without worrying about a body to clean up, and Kingsley finds out about this, tries to stop him, even with his memory psychosis, and in his last stand, publishes his study for the cure of cancer but including annotations about what this corporation has down to him.  In the end, to make it a serious ending, Kingsley in Reynolds body, would have to die.

text: This sounds a lot like a short story we read in high school (wish I could remember its title), about one girl's consciousness (as her brain)¬†being transferred to another girl's body. There was a bit of a twist, though, with her new body being an identical¬†twin. But it's really interesting to speculate on what would happen if the idea behind this movie and that story could eventually occur. Especially fascinating when you think about what it could prove or disprove about souls and the seat of consciousness. Is it really in the brain, or somewhere else? Looks like an interesting movie, if they do it right.
